1 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “DRUG DETECTION PRODUCT” MEANS A DISPOSABLE
2 TEST PRODUCT THAT ALLOWS AN INDIVIDUAL TO TEST A DRUG FOR THE PRESENCE
3 OF FENTANYL.
4 (B) EACH INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION SHALL PROVIDE, AT NO
5 CHARGE TO STUDENTS, DRUG DETECTION PRODUCTS.
6 (C) THE DRUG DETECTION PRODUCTS REQUIRED TO BE PROVIDED UNDER
7 THIS SECTION SHALL BE MADE AVAILABLE IN STUDENT HEALTH CENTERS,
8 LIBRARIES, AND BATHROOMS.
9 [11–1204.] 11–1205.
10 [(a)] On or before October 1 each year, each institution of higher education shall
11 report to the Commission on [each]:
12 (1) EACH incident at the institution that required the use of naloxone or
13 other overdose–reversing medication; AND
14 (2) THE QUANTITY OF DRUG DETECTION PRODUCTS DISTRIBUTED BY
15 THE INSTITUTION.
16 [(b) On or before December 1, 2018, December 1, 2019, and December 1, 2020, the
17 Commission shall report the information provided under subsection (a) of this section to
18 the General Assembly in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article.]
19 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
20 1, 2025.

